This paper deals with the analysis of tagged-magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) data to identify functional units of tongue behavior. This involves the use of matrix factorization and probabilistic graphical models, which are commonly used in computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the use of spectral clustering, which is a common technique in network analysis (cs.SI). Additionally, the paper has implications for the field of biomedical engineering (cs.BIO) as it can aid in surgical planning and rehabilitation procedures. Finally, the paper deals with the analysis of motion quantities, which is a common topic in neural engineering (cs.NE).
